#How a Transaction Becomes a Block ‚Äî Step-by-Step Process
1.Transaction Creation
A user initiates a transaction using a digital wallet.
The transaction includes:
‚Ä¢	Sender address
‚Ä¢	Receiver address
‚Ä¢	Amount/value
‚Ä¢	Transaction fee
‚Ä¢	Digital signature (created using the sender‚Äôs private key)
This signature proves ownership and authorization.
________________________________________
2.Transaction Broadcast
The signed transaction is broadcast to the peer-to-peer (P2P) blockchain network.
‚Ä¢	All nearby nodes receive the transaction
‚Ä¢	The transaction enters a temporary waiting area called the mempool
________________________________________
3.Transaction Validation by Nodes
Each node independently verifies the transaction by checking:
‚Ä¢	Valid digital signature
‚Ä¢	Sufficient account balance
‚Ä¢	Proper transaction format
‚Ä¢	No double spending
 Invalid transactions are rejected
Valid transactions remain in the mempool
________________________________________
4. Transaction Selection for a Block
Block producers (miners in PoW or validators in PoS):
‚Ä¢	Select verified transactions from the mempool
‚Ä¢	Usually prioritize transactions with higher fees
________________________________________
5. Block Formation
A new block is constructed containing:
‚Ä¢	Selected transactions
‚Ä¢	Previous block‚Äôs hash
‚Ä¢	Timestamp
‚Ä¢	Merkle root (summary hash of all transactions)
‚Ä¢	Nonce (PoW) or validator signature (PoS)
This links the block securely to the blockchain.
________________________________________
6. Consensus Process
üî® Proof of Work (PoW)
‚Ä¢	Miners compete to solve a cryptographic puzzle
‚Ä¢	The first to find a valid hash earns the right to add the block
üå± Proof of Stake (PoS)
‚Ä¢	A validator is selected based on stake and randomness
‚Ä¢	The validator proposes the block for approval
________________________________________
7. Block Verification by Network
Other nodes verify:
‚Ä¢	Block structure
‚Ä¢	Validity of all transactions
‚Ä¢	Correct hash or validator signature
If valid, the block is accepted.
________________________________________
8.Block Added to Blockchain
The verified block is added to the blockchain:
‚Ä¢	Becomes a permanent, immutable record
‚Ä¢	Linked cryptographically to previous blocks
________________________________________
9.Confirmation & Finality
‚Ä¢	Each new block added after it increases confirmation count
‚Ä¢	Higher confirmations = higher security
________________________________________
10. Reward Distribution
‚Ä¢	Miner or validator receives:
o	Block reward (if applicable)
o	Transaction fees
________________________________________
Key Takeaways
‚Ä¢	Transactions are verified before being included in blocks
‚Ä¢	Blocks are created through consensus mechanisms
‚Ä¢	Once added, blocks cannot be altered
‚Ä¢	This process ensures security, transparency, and trust
________________________________________

________________________________________
1. Banking Sector
Best-Fit Consensus:
Proof of Authority (PoA) / Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (PBFT)
(Permissioned Blockchain)
Why This Fits Banking
Banks operate in a regulated, permissioned environment:
‚Ä¢	Participants are known and verified
‚Ä¢	Transactions must be fast, final, and compliant
‚Ä¢	Data privacy is critical
Key Reasons
‚Ä¢	High throughput: Thousands of transactions per second
‚Ä¢	Immediate finality: No need for multiple confirmations
‚Ä¢	Low energy usage: No mining required
‚Ä¢	Strong identity control: Only approved banks validate blocks
Practical Usage
‚Ä¢	Interbank settlements
‚Ä¢	Cross-border payments
‚Ä¢	Trade finance
‚Ä¢	KYC data sharing
Examples
‚Ä¢	Hyperledger Fabric (PBFT-style)
‚Ä¢	R3 Corda (Notary-based consensus)
‚Ä¢	JP Morgan‚Äôs Onyx network
Why NOT PoW/PoS?
‚Ä¢	PoW ‚Üí too slow and energy-intensive
‚Ä¢	PoS ‚Üí unnecessary complexity and public exposure
________________________________________
2. Supply Chain Management
Best-Fit Consensus:
Proof of Authority (PoA) / PBFT / Raft
(Consortium Blockchain)
Why This Fits Supply Chain
Supply chains involve multiple known organizations:
‚Ä¢	Manufacturers
‚Ä¢	Transporters
‚Ä¢	Warehouses
‚Ä¢	Retailers
They need transparency + performance, not anonymity.
Key Reasons
‚Ä¢	Known validators: Verified companies
‚Ä¢	Fast confirmations: Real-time tracking
‚Ä¢	Low cost: No mining or staking
‚Ä¢	Controlled access: Protects business data
Practical Usage
‚Ä¢	Product traceability
‚Ä¢	Anti-counterfeit verification
‚Ä¢	Inventory tracking
‚Ä¢	Logistics automation
Examples
‚Ä¢	IBM Food Trust (Hyperledger Fabric)
‚Ä¢	Walmart supply chain blockchain
‚Ä¢	Maersk TradeLens
Why NOT PoW?
‚Ä¢	Slow transaction finality
‚Ä¢	High cost
‚Ä¢	No need for open participation
________________________________________
3. Government Records
Best-Fit Consensus:
Proof of Authority (PoA) / PBFT
(Permissioned or Hybrid Blockchain)
Why This Fits Government Records
Government data must be:
‚Ä¢	Tamper-proof
‚Ä¢	Auditable
‚Ä¢	Legally accountable
‚Ä¢	Private but verifiable
Key Reasons
‚Ä¢	Validators are government departments
‚Ä¢	High trust requirement
‚Ä¢	Clear accountability
‚Ä¢	Compliance with legal frameworks
Practical Usage
‚Ä¢	Land records
‚Ä¢	Identity management
‚Ä¢	Birth & death certificates
‚Ä¢	Voting systems
‚Ä¢	Court documents
Examples
‚Ä¢	Estonia e-Governance blockchain
‚Ä¢	India‚Äôs land registry pilots
‚Ä¢	Dubai Blockchain Strategy
Why NOT Public Consensus?
‚Ä¢	PoW/PoS expose data publicly
‚Ä¢	Lack of legal identity control
‚Ä¢	Regulatory challenges
________________________________________
Summary Comparison Table
Sector	Best Consensus	Blockchain Type	Reason
Banking	PoA / PBFT	Permissioned	Speed, compliance, trust
Supply Chain	PoA / PBFT	Consortium	Transparency + performance
Government Records	PoA / PBFT	Permissioned/Hybrid	Accountability, auditability
________________________________________
Key Takeaways
‚Ä¢	Public blockchains are best for open finance
‚Ä¢	Permissioned consensus fits enterprise & government
‚Ä¢	Speed, identity, and legal compliance matter more than decentralization in these sectors
